410→                           The colouring version of this is <a href="/303" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[303]</a>, which was solved by Brown and Rödl <a href="#cite-BrRo91-302" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('BrRo91','302'); return false;">[BrRo91]</a>. One can take either $A$ to be all odd integers in $[1,N]$ or all integers in $[N/2,N]$ to show $f(N)\geq (1/2+o(1))N$.<br><br>Wouter van Doorn has proved (see <a href="https://github.com/Woett/Mathematical-shorts/blob/main/Two-colouring%20and%20density%20lead%20to%20solutions%20to%20an%20equation%20in%20unit%20fractions.pdf" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">this note</a>) that\[f(N) \leq (9/10+o(1))N.\]Stijn Cambie has observed that\[f(N)\geq (5/8+o(1))N,\]taking $A$ to be all odd integers $\leq N/4$ and all integers in $[N/2,N]$.<br><br>Stijn Cambie has also observed that, if we allow $b=c$, then there is a solution to this equation when $\lvert A\rvert \geq (\tfrac{2}{3}+o(1))N$, since then there must exist some $n,2n\in A$.<br><br>See also <a href="/301" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[301]</a> and <a href="/327" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[327]</a>.
